“How can HTCondor be used for economics?” asked Dr. Kenneth Judd, Senior Fellow at the Hoover Institution, when he presented his work on using high throughput computing (HTC) to model climate policy, and how the field of economics can utilize HTC. While presenting at [High Throughput Computing Week 2026](https://agenda.hep.wisc.edu/event/2432/overview) (HTC26), Judd shared that he first started using HTC and [HTCondor](https://htcondor.org/), a workload management and job scheduling system developed by the [Center for High Throughput Computing](https://chtc.cs.wisc.edu/) (CHTC), in his research work 20 years ago. This connection to CHTC followed after he realized that there were no comparable resources available at Stanford for his Stanford PhD student. Judd reached out to CHTC Director Miron Livny, who directed the provision of OSPool “unlimited access at zero priority” to HTCondor.

